One film that had a profound impact on my understanding of racial inequality is "13th," directed by Ava DuVernay. This powerful documentary dives deep into the history of racial discrimination in America, tracing the journey from slavery to today's prison-industrial complex. What resonated with me the most was how effectively it highlights the systemic racism that continues to perpetuate cycles of oppression.

DuVernay masterfully blends historical context with contemporary statistics, weaving a compelling narrative that exposes the intricate ties between race and the criminal justice system. The film's rich use of expert interviews and archival footage paints a vivid yet sobering picture of how policies disproportionately affect marginalized communities.

Watching "13th" opened my eyes to the complexities of social justice issues and deepened my awareness of the importance of advocating for meaningful reform. It inspired me to think more critically about these topics and motivated me to actively seek solutions to combat systemic inequities. If you haven’t seen it yet, I highly recommend giving it a watch;
